{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_evans_ver01/data/sn86063730/00332894195/1930021902/0343.xml":{"full_text":"\u00ae!P Snramsuttlc Heralfl\nEstablished July 4, 1892\nEntered as second-class matter in the Postoffice\nBrownsville Texas.\nTHE BROWNSVILLE HERALD PUBLISHING\nCOMPANY\nSubscription Rates\u2014Daily and Sunday (7 Issues)\nOne Year .$9.00\nBlx Months\nThree Months. $2.25\nDne Month. .75\nMEMBER OP TUE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nThe Associated Press Is exclusively entitled to the use\nfor publication of all news dispatches credited to It or\nnot otherwise credited In this paper, and also the\nlocal news published herein.\nHarlingen Office. Reese-WU-Mond Hotel. Phone 1020.\nTEXAS DAILY PRESS LEAGUE\nNational Advertising Representatives\nDallas, Texas, 512 Mercantile Bank Building.\nKansas City, Mo., 306 Coca Cola Building.\nChicago, I1U Association Building.\nNew York, 350 Madison Avenue.\nSt. Louis, 502 Star Building.\nLos Angeles, Cal., Room 1015 New Orpheum Bldg.,\n#46 8. Broadway,\nSan Francisco, Cal.. 318 Kohl Building.\nAnother Terrell in the Picture\nThere is another Terrell in tne picture. This tune\nit is J. T. Terrell of Del Rio. He is a newly elected\nmember of the house, coming from the 87th district.\nHis father Is state commissioner of agriculture.\nThere have been Terrells in the house time and\nagain. There have been Terrells in the senate. There\nwas a Terrell speaker in the not remote past. There\nare Terrells everywhere in Texas.\nGeorge B., the commissioner, had long service In\nthe house. Now he is going back to the farm.\nSamuel Houston Terrell, is in the picture, too. Think\nof a state where the comptroller of accounts receives\nan annual salary of less than $2500 a year; where the\ncommissioner of the land office receives a like sal\nary and handles a billion dollars worth of state\nproperty; where a state treasurer receives the pay\nof a clerk and handles millions of cash and is the\nguardian of hundreds of millions of securities.\nThere Is another picture\u2014a state where county of\nficers are paid as high as $20,000 a year in salary\nand fees and where a Justice of the peace has a\nmore lucrative salary than the governor of the com\nmonwealth.\nWhere the People Believe in\nHighways\nCameron county, on the banks of the Rio Grande\nriver, is in the picture again. Cameron county com\nmissioners voted a $6,000,000 bond issue of the county\nroad paving program. Brownsville Is the metropolis\nof Cameron and Brownsville Is a fast growing city,\nand the rural districts of the county are listed as\nplaces where the fruit growers and the vegetable\ngrowers know how to make rich yearly dividends.\nNot many years ago Cameron county had a very\nsmall place on the map. Now it has an Important\nplace. Men and money performed the seeming mir\nacle.\u2014Austin Statesman.\nWhy Norris Fought Hughes\nSen. George W. Norris Is a grim fighter and an\nIndependent thinker and voter. In the closing hour\nsf a remarkable contest, the Nebraska senator said:\n\"Charles Evans Hughes Is not fit to sit in Judg\nment in the contest between organized wealth and\nthose who toil.\u201d\nThis was a voice from the west. Following his\nconfirmation as chief Justice of the supreme court,\nCharles Evans Hughes issued a statement In which\nhe said:\n\"The ideals and principles relating to public ser\nvice with which I entered public life 25 years ago\nand which I have tried to exemplify In public of\nfice I hold unaltered.\u201d\nThis must be taken as a voice from the east.\nRadio in the Billion Dollar Class\nRadio dealers to the number of 500 held a confer\nence in the city of Cleveland to formulate defi\nnite plans to put themselves in the billion dollar\nclass in 1930 for the first time. In 1929 the radio\nbusiness amounted to $850,000,000 and this year will\nsee it In the $1,000,000,000 elass. Now why should the\nfarm boy desert the farm?\nIF BABE RUTH QUITS BASEBALL\n(Copyright, 1930, by The Associated Newspapers.)\n(Scene 1\u2014A room In the Babe\u2019s apartment around\nDecoration Day. Ruth is sitting disconsolately in a\nchair. Mrs. Ruth enters waving check.)\nRuth: What's that?\nMrs. Ruth: Another dividend. That makes more\nthan $2,500 we\u2019ve got on our Investments this month.\nLovely, isn\u2019t it?\nRuth: Yeah. Where arc they playing today?\nMrs. Ruth: Who?,\nRuth: The Yanks.\nMrs. Ruth: I haven\u2019t the slightest idea. Are you\nstill thinking about baseball? I thought you were\na retired business man.\nRuth: Well I am. but I think about the old\ngame once in a while.\n(The phone rings. Mrs. Ruth answers it.)\nRuth (after she hangs up): Who was that, honey?\nMrs. Ruth: That was Mr. Glootz. the broker. He\nsays you\u2019ve made $10,000 on that steel stock and he's\nsending you a check. Great, isnt It?\nRuth: Who\u2019s pitching?\nMrs. Ruth: I say he's sending check for $10.\n000. Isn\u2019t It nice?\nRuth: I\u2019ll bet they\u2019ve got some bum playing right\nfield.\nMrs. Ruth: Do get your mind off baseball, dear.\nHere\u2019s a letter for you.\nRuth: Read It.\nMrs. Ruth: It's the contract from the circus\npeople. They want to sign you up for $50,000 a year\nJust to appear with the show a few minutes twice a\nday. How wonderful!\nRuth: The trouble is there\u2019s no team-work.\nMrs. Ruth: In the circus?\nRuth: With the Yanks. I mean They should\nhave won them last two games.\nMrs. Ruth: You promised me you wouldn\u2019t think\nany more about the Yanks after you retired.\nRuth: I'm not thinking about them. They're off\nmy mind entirely.\nMrs. Ruth: You mustn\u2019t give them a thought.\nRuth: Not a thought. I should worry what be\ncomes of those birds.\nMrs. Ruth: That\u2019s the spirit!\nRuth: But they shouldn't be dropping games the\nway they are. They should murder that kind of\npitching. Why in the elvhth inning\nMrs. Ruth: Please. Babe, you're out of baseball\nand money Is rolling in from other sources and we're\nvery comfortable. Aren\u2019t you happy?\nRuth: Of course I'm happy?\nMrs. Ruth: That\u2019s fine.\nRuth: But they're not socking the old pill.\nMrs Ruth 'exasperated!: Dear, why must you go\non talking about baseball? Anybody would think\nyou were sorry you had quit the game and would give\nanything to be back with the Yankees.\nRuth: Well they\u2019d be D- RIGHT!\nHint to ex-Govemor Alfred E. Smith: Lissen. Al.\ndon't fall for all those clowning stunts suggested to\nyou by these news reel men. They must be working\nfor the Republican party.\nThe Department of Commerce announces with a\nglow of pride that the United States leads the world\nas a producer of false teeth. But somehow or other\nit's hard to get the little boys and girls to burst into\nan orgy of flag-waving over that.\n\nHow do we stand in the glass eye Industry? And.\nnow that our curiosity is aroused, can it be true that\nAmerica has dropped to third place in the interna\ntional league as a manufacturer of false mustaches?\nMORE EVIDENCE FOR FADLOCKERS\nAmong the many proofs that there is a less than\nlukewarm support of the dry law is the fact that\nmost of the new hotels In the country have a com\nbination corkscrew and cap-remover attached to the\nwall.\nChicago authorities ordered a round-up of all gun\nmen and thugs the other day. Probably for a news\nreel or something.\nTHE OLD HOME TOWN.Stanley\n(OTEX THAT\nSTUFF SMEI-LS\nsneoNC, enough/\nTO TAKE ~Th' y\nHAIR OFF\nQ\nf-\\\nWHEW- IT\nSMELLS LIKE\nTUPN1P MASH\nWITH AH\nAPH1CA BASByl\nAND A DASH\nOF CHEAP\nPAINT\n\nC\\ C5UESS\nI \u201cTHAT iL\nB^EAK UP\n\u25a0mis <SAN<*\nOF POISON\nPEPPLERS!\nr-^\nTHEY \"THINK \u00bbTS\nTH' SAME STUFF!\nSAM SNODGRASS\nDRANK -TH' NIGHT\nHE KICKED TH F\u00ae\n\\S\u00a3 CONCRETE\n^3 HORSE TROUGH]\nQj\u00b0_^fe!y\nlO\nC-*'C fi\nv*?; <c\n\nDont\n<5ET n-<-:\nON\nT'OLR.\nCLOTHE-'\nOTEY!'.\nMARSHAL OTEY WALKER NOT ONLY SCARED\nTHAT STRANGER, WHEN WE COASTED\nRK3HT UNDER HIM ON ICE HOUSE HILL, I\n8l>T ME CAU<qMT THE FELLER WHO HAS\nFLOODED THESE PARTS WITH THE WORST I\nSTUFF EVER PUT UNDER A CORK\np^THElQVp ?Pat\nBv CLWkBD \u00a91999\nCHAPTER 48\nThe vagaries of the average young\nwoman\u2019s heart, proclaim the ex\nperts. are many. True love, they\nsay, hath a way for Mary Hath\naway that for Susie Boles it hath\nnot.\nWithout a well developed sense\nof humor. Margery Lynne would\nnot have fallen in love with Jimmy\nBlair under the rather remarkable\ncircumstances that prevailed. It\nwas pity first, then knowledge of\nthe heroic deed that had brought\nabout his Injury, the romanticism\nattached to his kidnaping and af\nterward acquaintance and liking\nfor Pat.\nThrough It all, like the main\nthread in a fabric, ran the amus\ning motion that she might win Jim\nmy's love without his knowledge,\nduring the period of his sub-con\nsciousness, and when he was him\nself again\u2014for Margery never\ndoubted but what Jimmy would\neventually \"pick up the lost chord\u201d\n\u2014he would recognize in her. his\naffinity. None but a humorously in\nclined, highly developed imagina\ntion ever could have followed with\nsuch pertinacity of purpose, the\nline of thought that Margery con\nsistently pursued And It was ow\ning to her own Ingenuous way of\nlooking at life, and living, that\nshe was able to obtain the Joy she\ndid out of her daily association\nwith Jimmy and Pat.\nDuring the first forty-eight hours\nafter leaving New York the chill\nair of late February kept Pat and\nher friends a greater part of the\ntime within the comfortable con\nfines of the yacht's commodious\ncabin. A piano and a talking ma\nchine furnished music for dancing\nin the evening, and in dancing,\neating, talking card-playing and\nsleeping the hours flitted past so\nswiftly they could hardly realize\nthe cruise was nearly two days old j\nand that the Bluebird had made a\nrun of 700 miles.\nMargery and Lucy, coming Into\nthe cabin after a brisk exercise\njaunt around the ship\u2019s promenade\ndecks Informed the half dozen still\nsitting around the breakfast table\nthat \u201cthe weather outside Is as\nsoft and balmy as a day in June!\u201d\n\"Then It's me for the \u2018soft and\nbalmy!\u2019\u201d averred Rex, hoping as\nhe spoke that the \u201cone girl\u201d would\nexpress a like intention.\nWhich the \u201cone girl\u201d did-But\nDr. Frank Gordon, on the following\nInstant expressed himself also as i\nbeing seized with a craving for the\nocean breeze. Not only that, but\nhe addressed his intention direct\nly to the \"one girl\u201d with the add\nIT _ i\nGrab Bag i|\ni in\nFebruary 19, 1930\nWho am I? What is my profes\nsion? Where are my headquarters?\nWhat city in the United States\nhad a famous trial revolving around\nthe teaching of evolution?\nWhat color Is usually associated\nwith kings?\n\u201cMasters, give unto your servants\nthat which is Just and equal;\nknowing that ye also have a master\nin heaven.\" Where is this passage\nfound in the Bible?\nCorrectly Speaking\u2014\nBe sure that your similes and\nmetaphors are in keeping with the\nexpression preceding. Don't say,\nThe police drag net has uncorked\nseveral criminals.\u201d \u201cThe police drag\nnet has ensnared or caught several\ncriminals.\" is correct.\nToday\u2019s Anniversary\nOn this day. in 1803, Ohio was\nadmitted to the union.\nToday's Horoscope\nPersons born on this day arc\nstrong characters and rise above\ntheir surroundings.\nAnswers to Foregoing Questions\n1 Merle Thorpe: magazine editor;\nWashington, D. C.\n2. Dayton, Tenn.\n3. Purple.\n4. Colosslans. lv. 1.\n1 Star Lore\nTHE FEBRUARY EVENING\nSKY\nBy Arthur DeV. Carpenter\nAlong the belt of the Zodiac\n(ar.imal belt) of the evening sky\n.his month, beginning at the far\nwest ari tracing eastward, arc\nArles. Taurus, Cc.ninl Cancer and\nI These ta e us over the dome\nof the hr avers and to the east.\nTill ore becomes familiar with\nthese conspicuous constellations, a\nsimpler star char: like Baton's\nGuide to the Constellation* is need\nel. Gmlri is nearly overhead, dis\ntin::. hod by two bright stars\nmarking the heads of the Twins\nThe brightest is Polux; the other\nis Castor. Orion, the most magni\nficent of all the constellations. Is\na little to the west of the meridian.\nSirius, the \"Dog Star.\" brightest\nstar in the sky, is south on meri\ndian.\n(More Tomorrow),\ned suggestion that they go after\nthe breeze In company. And since,\nas the old saying has it, \u201ctwo is\ncompany, but three Is a crowd.\"\nthe lieutenant\u2019s desire for the \u2018soft\nand balmy\u2019 died virtually in its\nhorning.\nWhile there had been no word\nspoken on the subject by either man\nsince the brief talk in the taxicab,\nthe heretofore mentioned gentle\nmen's agreement\u201d anent Pat and\nthe \u201clove game\u201d second, in some\nway or another, by some sort of\ntelepathically mutual understand\ning. to have been ejected into the\nlimbo of discarded things. The\nbarriers, obviously, had been rais\ned: It was now each man for him\nself.\nIn his character of a friend. Dr.\nPrank Gordon was closer to Rex\nDallard than any other living man.\nDuring their few months of in\ntimate association he had come to\nknow and like the young doctor\nror his many lovable qualities. He\nknew that Gordon was what he\ncalled a \u201csquare shooter.\u201d He knew,\ntoo. that in addition to being a\n\"square shooter\u201d the other was of\na generous, broadminded and al\ntogether unselfish nature, the kind\nof a man who takes real pleasure In\nhelping others even when the help\ning entails a sacrifice on his part.\nAnd yet. despite all this and\nmore, despite the fact that he liked\nGordon above all men and knew\nthat Gordon liked him. probably,\nequally as well, he told himself as\nhe watched this friend-rival pass\nout of the cabin with the \"one girl\u201d\nthat he wished, mast heartily wish\ned that \u201cthe cuss would fall down\nand break his neck!\u201d\nRex Dallard did not. of cours?\nwish any such thing. He did wish,\nhowever, honestly and conscientious\nly. that the doctor could transfer\nhis affections to some girl other\nthan Pat\u2014to Lucy Pine, for in\nstance Lucy. Rex was sure, would\nmake Gordon a wonderful wife.\nOddly enough Dr. Prank Gordon,\njust the day before, had told him\nself almost identically the same\nthing only he had named Rex Dal\nlard for Lucy.\nBut Patr-what did she think of\nthem? That was the question Rex\nwas the most disturbed about. In\njust what light was Gordon held he\nwondered. In what light was he.\nRex Dallard. held by this girl for\nwhom he stood ready at any mo\nment, if the need presented itself, to\ngive up his very life? How\u2019 did she\nconsider him? Did she like either\none, Gordon or himseif any better\nthan the other? She knew of course\nthat both of them were deeply in\nlove with her. A woman always\nknows whether a man loves her or\nnet. If she c}id like one of them a\nlittle the best, which was it?\nP.cx had told himself tiir.3 with\nout number that nothing would ever\ninduce him to ask Pat for Blair\u2019s\nhand in marriage. She had too much\nmoney, had been his cry to himself.\nSince Jimmy's restoration, however\nhis ideas had undergone something\nof a revision. He no longer felt so\ndetermined in regard to the money\nquestion. And anyhow that was an\nafter consideration. The important\nquestion now was: Did she give an\neternal hoot for either of them, Gor\ndon or he? If so, which?\nThat was the vital consideration\nright now. Did she care a tinker\u2019s\ndarn for either of them and if so\n\u2014which?\nHe cruld of course ask her. But\nwould that get him anything\u2014or\nanywhere? Wouldn\u2019t it be a fool\nthing to do\u2014to percipitate matters\nby putting such question to her\nbluntly\u2014without any reason what\nsoever for thinking she cared for\nhim? If she ever had. or ever would\ngive him any sign, any excuse to\nhope, then he would be justified.\nBut until she did offer him some\nthing on which to feed a decent\nhope, his best plan of attack., to use\na soldier\u2019s phrase was \u201cwatchful\nwaiting.\u201d\nHaving arrived at this very sen\nsible conclusion, Rex felt much bet\nter. And since feeling better was\nequivalent to feeling fit, he felt the\nimmediate need of a little exercise\nin the open air.\nReaching the main deck he look\ned forward and saw tliat which both\npuzzled and astonished him. Stand\ning close to the port rail Just oppo\nsite the pilot house were Margery\nand Jimmy Blair. The latter was\nleaning in a careless, perfectly na\ntural man\u2019s posfc against the rail\nand gazing, apparently, straight in\nto the eyes of the girl, who stood\ndirectly in front of him. That which\nhad struck Rex with such wonder\nment was the incontrovertible fact\nthat Margery was talking, fast, ea:\nnestly and directly to Jimmy; talk\ning in Just the same manner sli\nmight have been talking had lit\nRex. or Dr. Gordon been standin\nIn front of her instead of Jim in;,\nAnd the latter seemed at the same\ntime to be listening. It was too mucl\nRex assured himself. He moved to\nward the pair.\n\u201cYou don t mean to tell me, Mar\nSAMBO\u2019S PHILOSOPHY\n\u201cDat preachnh done invite hisse\u2019f\navah to er chicken dlnnah touior\nrer\u2014an' hits a FULL AJuO.N Xei\ntoah mo\u2019 nights yit I\u201d\nTHE MODERN LORELEI!\ngery,\" he 6a ;d as he came within\neasy speaking distance, \u201cthat Jimmy\nhas\u2014\u201c\nShe had turned at the first sound\nof his voice. Ker face flushed and\nher eyes sparkled. She cut Into his\nquery with a ripple of laughter ad\na quick answer.\n\u201cJimmy's having the time of his\nyoung life, he says!\u201d .she declared\nwith the most guileless air of cheer\nful insouciance possible to imagine.;\nThe one thing that bothers him is\nthat he hasn't the slightest idea in\nthe world what I'm talking about!\nBut that doesn\u2019t matter in the\nicast. The important thing is that\nhe likes being talked to. It doesn\u2019t\nof course, make any difference to\nhim what you talk about. Just so\nit is talk and is being addressed to\nnim. I discovered the little fact\nyesterday and spoke to Pat about\nit. She thinks just as I do\u2014that\nsince he likes it we ought all of us\nto talk to him\u2014talk Just as we do\nto each other and as If he under\nstood us!\u201d\niTO BE CONTINUED)\nS. M. U. Debaters\nTo Have Varied Meet\nDALLAS, Feb. 19\u2014Two triangular I\ndebates and six dual arguments are\non the 1930 debate schedule of\nSouthern Methodist university.\nGraduate students will participate\nin two of the debates, that with\nLouisiana State here March 15.\nwhich will open the season, and that\nATTENTION!\nX We have added a I\nX Rental Library to our 1\nX store! Come in and look\nI it over. All of the best I\nsellers of all publishers, tj\nKeep abreast of the J\nmost popular new books\nX by renting them at\nX small cost!\nE HARGROVE\u2019S tj\nI Stationery Book Store\nX Phone 348\nBrownsville, Texas\nGet poisons out\nof system.\nDoctors know that\nthis modern scientific laxative\nworks efficiently in smaller\ndoses because you chew it.\nSafe and mild for old and young.\nFeenamint\ni m\nI 1\nwith Emory university of Atlanta\nhere.\nTriangular meets have been ar\nranged with Hendrix college, Con\nway, Ark., and Southwestern uni\nversity of Georgetown April 11 and\nwith A. and M. and T. C. U. on a\ndate yet to be fixed. In the trian\ngular meets, each of the schools will j\nbe represented by two teams, which'\nwill debate teams with the other\nschools.\nOther dual debates will be with\nthe University of California here.\nTulane here, Colorado at Boulder\nand Oklahoma.\nItaly's 26 plants for the produc\ntion of artificial silk had an r\nput of 62,855.448 pounds for the\nfirst nine months of 1929. A gain\nover the previous year\u2019s output of\n44.481,855 pounds.\nMeat products turned out by Cali\nfornia packers In 1929 were valued\nat $125,000,000.\nEat At\n*0\nAnthony\u2019* Waffle\nShop\n517 12 St Phone 983\nA. TAMM\nBlue Printing and\nSupplies\nHarlingen, Texas\n1911 1930\nSkelton Abstract Co.\nAbstracts of Title\nMerchants Bank Building\nTitle Insurance\nBrownsville\nCARNEIRO, CHUMNEY COMPANY\nCertified Public Accountants\nIncome Tax Sendee\nBROWNSVILLE PAN ANTONIO CORPUS CHRIST1\nState National Bank Smith-Young Tower Nixon Building\n\u2014PROSPERITY^\nProsperity for Brownsville and\nthe Valley is a tangible, able-to\nbe-seen condition. Citrus groves\nare beginning to bloom vege\ntables are commanding good\nprices generally the interna\ntional airport .and the bright\n;rrospects for a deep water port\u2014\nall are encouraging a splendit\nbusiness outlook for Brownsville\nand the Valley.\nLet us, as your bank, help\nyou with any problems you\nmay wish to discuss with us.\nFirst National Bank\ni\nEstablished in 1891\nBROWNSVILLE, TEXAS\n\nTITLE INSURANCE\nWhen you borrow money on real estate, many loan companies re\nquire the title to tie insured. The best lest of whether a title is\ninsurable, is to have it insured. Require a title insurance policy\nwhen you buy.\nVALLEY ABSTRACT COMPANY\nPrompt Title Service\nBrownsville\nOpposite Court House\nPbone 1184\nFdinburjc\nK. Harriman Blvd.\nI'hone 93","height":"36428","width":"27448"}}
